{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658699"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20811"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20811"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96963"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13686"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79578"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11579"},{"type":"tags","id":"12644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32962"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96963"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGenetic recombination occurs in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes, contributing to genetic diversity and DNA repair mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of homologous recombination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Exchange of genetic material between similar DNA sequences","Random insertion of DNA fragments into the genome","Direct substitution of nucleotides without DNA strand breaks","Enzymatic alteration of histones to modify gene expression","Specific DNA cleavage by restriction endonucleases"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHomologous recombination involves the \u003Cstrong\u003Eexchange of genetic material between similar DNA sequences\u003C/strong\u003E. The process begins when a double-strand break occurs in DNA, followed by 5\u0027 to 3\u0027 resection creating single-stranded DNA tails. In prokaryotes, RecA protein (or Rad51 in eukaryotes) coats these single-stranded regions and facilitates strand invasion into a homologous DNA molecule. This forms a displacement loop (D-loop), enabling DNA synthesis using the homologous sequence as a template. The process concludes with resolution of Holliday junctions, completing the genetic exchange.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom insertion of DNA fragments into the genome\u003C/strong\u003E - This would be non-homology dependent and lacks the sequence specificity characteristic of homologous recombination\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect substitution of nucleotides without DNA strand breaks\u003C/strong\u003E - Homologous recombination fundamentally requires DNA strand breakage to initiate the process\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnzymatic alteration of histones to modify gene expression\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes epigenetic mechanisms rather than genetic recombination\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpecific DNA cleavage by restriction endonucleases\u003C/strong\u003E - While these enzymes cut DNA at specific sites, they do not mediate the exchange of genetic material\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHomologous recombination has crucial biological functions including repairing double-strand breaks, restarting stalled replication forks, and generating genetic diversity during meiosis through crossing over. This mechanism is evolutionarily conserved and essential for genomic stability.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Homologous recombination is a DNA repair mechanism that exchanges genetic material between similar or identical DNA sequences.","Crossing over during meiosis is a form of homologous recombination that increases genetic diversity in offspring.","Homologous recombination requires the RecA/Rad51 protein family to catalyse strand invasion and exchange."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease; p. 6"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79578"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20811"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79578"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T22:38:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T22:40:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13686"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96963"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11578"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"The cell as a unit of health and disease","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":0,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11579"},"attri